<body>
<div id="scrollbar"></div>

<header id="topbar">
  <button id="menuBtn" aria-label="Open menu">☰</button>
  <span class="b">The Architecture of Story</span>
</header>
<div id="overlay"></div>

<div class="app">
  <!-- ===================== SIDEBAR ===================== -->
  <aside id="sidebar">
    <div class="brand" data-go="home">
      <p class="k">Creative Writing · Narrative Craft</p>
      <h1>The Architecture<br>of Story</h1>
      <div class="ring">
        <svg width="34" height="34" viewBox="0 0 34 34"><circle cx="17" cy="17" r="14" fill="none" stroke="var(--rule)" stroke-width="4"/><circle id="ringfg" cx="17" cy="17" r="14" fill="none" stroke="var(--teal)" stroke-width="4" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-dasharray="88" stroke-dashoffset="88" transform="rotate(-90 17 17)"/></svg>
        <span id="ringtxt">0 of 10 lessons<br>complete</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="searchwrap"><input id="search" type="text" placeholder="search the course…" autocomplete="off" spellcheck="false"></div>
    <nav id="nav" aria-label="Course navigation"></nav>
    <div class="navfoot"><button id="resetBtn">↺ Reset progress</button><span>Progress is saved locally in this browser.</span></div>
  </aside>

  <!-- ===================== MAIN ===================== -->
  <main id="main">

    <!-- ============ HOME ============ -->
    <section class="module" id="home" data-title="Course Map">
      <div class="inner wide">
        <div class="home-hero">
          <p class="k">A Guide to Creative Writing &amp; Narrative Structure</p>
          <h2>The Architecture<br>of Story</h2>
          <p class="sf">Learn how stories are built — from the first principle to the finished draft.</p>
          <div class="fleuron">❦</div>
        </div>

        <div class="bigquote">A story is a system in which a character under pressure makes choices — and those choices <strong>change them.</strong></div>

        <div class="maptitle">The five laws beneath everything</div>
        <div class="laws">
          <div class="law"><div class="ln">1</div><div class="lt">Therefore, not “and then”</div><div class="ld">Every beat is caused by the last.</div></div>
          <div class="law"><div class="ln">2</div><div class="lt">Conflict is story</div><div class="ld">No obstacle, no story.</div></div>
          <div class="law"><div class="ln">3</div><div class="lt">Want vs. Need</div><div class="ld">Meaning lives in the gap.</div></div>
          <div class="law"><div class="ln">4</div><div class="lt">Show, don’t tell</div><div class="ld">Render through sense &amp; act.</div></div>
          <div class="law"><div class="ln">5</div><div class="lt">Finish the draft</div><div class="ld">Done beats perfect.</div></div>
        </div>

        <div class="maptitle">The course, end to end</div>
        <div class="map" id="coursemap"><!-- built by JS --></div>

        <div class="maptitle">Pick a path</div>
        <div class="paths">
          <div class="pathcard">
            <h4>I’m writing a short story</h4>
            <p class="pm">One episode, one emotion. Tight constraints.</p>
            <div class="plinks"><span class="pl" data-go="first-principles">First Principles</span><span class="pl" data-go="conflict">Conflict</span><span class="pl" data-go="forms">The Short Story</span><span class="pl" data-go="craft">Craft</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="pathcard">
            <h4>I’m writing a novel</h4>
            <p class="pm">The long game — arcs, subplots, momentum.</p>
            <div class="plinks"><span class="pl" data-go="character">Character</span><span class="pl" data-go="structure">Structure</span><span class="pl" data-go="process">The Process</span><span class="pl" data-go="revision">Revision</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="pathcard">
            <h4>I’m writing a screenplay</h4>
            <p class="pm">Behaviour only — the camera can’t hear thoughts.</p>
            <div class="plinks"><span class="pl" data-go="structure">Save the Cat</span><span class="pl" data-go="craft">Dialogue</span><span class="pl" data-go="forms">The Screenplay</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="homenote">✎ Every lesson ends with a “Your turn” workbook. Your answers, ticked checklists, and progress all save automatically in this browser.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
    <section class="module" id="first-principles" data-title="First Principles" data-phase="Foundations" data-lesson="1">
      <div class="inner">
        <div class="mhead"></div>
        <p class="lead">Before any framework, four truths. Every technique in this course is downstream of them — if you remember only this lesson, you can still write a real story.</p>

        <h3 id="fp-def"><span class="h3n">1.1</span>What a story actually is</h3>
        <p>Strip away genre, length, and medium and every story reduces to one thing:</p>
        <div class="bigquote">A character wants something. Something <strong>stands in the way.</strong> The pursuit forces choices that change them — or fail to.</div>
        <p>That is the irreducible core. A travelogue of events is <em>not</em> a story; a character pursuing a goal against resistance <strong>is</strong>. Every element you’ll learn exists to serve that core.</p>

        <h3 id="fp-cause"><span class="h3n">1.2</span>Causality: “therefore,” not “and then”</h3>
        <p>The single most useful rule of thumb in storytelling. A weak plot is a list of events. A strong plot is a chain of consequences. Watch the difference:</p>
        <div class="card">
          <p style="margin:0 0 6px;font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px;letter-spacing:.1em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--ink-faint)">A sequence — flat</p>
          <div class="chain weak"><span class="chnode">This</span><span class="chlink">and then</span><span class="chnode">that</span><span class="chlink">and then</span><span class="chnode">that</span></div>
          <p style="margin:16px 0 6px;font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px;letter-spacing:.1em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--red)">A story — driven</p>
          <div class="chain strong"><span class="chnode">This</span><span class="chlink">therefore →</span><span class="chnode">that</span><span class="chlink">but →</span><span class="chnode">this</span></div>
        </div>
        <p>Each event must be the <strong>consequence of a character’s choice</strong>, not a random next thing. Causality is what produces suspense. When you outline, audit every join: if only “and then” fits, you have a sequence, not a story.</p>

        <h3 id="fp-conflict"><span class="h3n">1.3</span>Conflict <em>is</em> story</h3>
        <p>Every story, underneath, asks one question:</p>
        <div class="bigquote">Will the protagonist overcome their obstacles to <strong>get what they want?</strong></div>
        <p>Remove the obstacle and you remove the story. Conflict isn’t a flaw to minimise — it is the thing the reader came for.</p>

        <h3 id="fp-wantneed"><span class="h3n">1.4</span>Want vs. Need — where meaning comes from</h3>
        <p>The deepest engine in fiction is the gap between what a character chases and what they actually require.</p>
        <div class="engine">
          <div class="pole want"><div class="lbl">Want · external</div><h4>What they think they want</h4><p>A concrete, pursuable goal. Drives the plot. Often built on a lie they tell themselves.</p></div>
          <div class="arrow"><div class="big">⇢</div><span class="cap">the story<br>closes the gap</span></div>
          <div class="pole need"><div class="lbl">Need · internal</div><h4>What they actually need</h4><p>A deeper truth about themselves or the world. Drives the arc. Learning it unlocks the ending.</p></div>
        </div>
        <p>The classic shape: chase the <strong>Want</strong>, discover it rested on a lie, learn the <strong>Need</strong>. <em>Inside Out’s</em> Joy <em>wants</em> Riley always happy; she <em>needs</em> to learn every emotion matters. Gatsby <em>wants</em> Daisy; he <em>needs</em> to learn the past can’t be bought — and never learns it (a negative arc). External plot and internal growth aren’t two things; they’re one engine seen from two sides.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============ 2 · ELEMENTS ============ -->
    <section class="module" id="elements" data-title="The Seven Elements" data-phase="Foundations" data-lesson="2">
      <div class="inner">
        <div class="mhead"></div>
        <p class="lead">If first principles are the physics, these are the parts list — the seven components nearly every story is assembled from. Each gets its own job; the load-bearing ones get their own lessons.</p>
        <div class="cardgrid cg-3">
          <div class="card"><span class="tag both">why you write it</span><h4>Theme</h4><p>The idea or feeling underneath — usually the truth your protagonist’s <em>Need</em> points toward. Don’t state it; weave it through and let readers find it.</p></div>
          <div class="card"><span class="tag int">the life-force</span><h4>Character</h4><p>Personalities and their collisions generate conflict and drive plot. <a class="inl" data-go="character">Lesson 3 →</a></p></div>
          <div class="card"><span class="tag ext">the world</span><h4>Setting</h4><p>Time, place, institutions. Deliver it in drips woven through action, never in dumps.</p></div>
          <div class="card"><span class="tag ext">what happens</span><h4>Plot</h4><p>Rising stakes toward an inevitable climax, bound by the law of causality. <a class="inl" data-go="structure">Lesson 5 →</a></p></div>
          <div class="card"><span class="tag both">the tension</span><h4>Conflict</h4><p>Internal, external, or both — the source of all momentum. <a class="inl" data-go="conflict">Lesson 4 →</a></p></div>
          <div class="card"><span class="tag int">the lens</span><h4>Point of View</h4><p>Whose eyes we watch through — it changes intimacy, reliability, even which story gets told. <a class="inl" data-go="craft">Lesson 7 →</a></p></div>
          <div class="card"><span class="tag both">your voice</span><h4>Style</h4><p>Pacing, tone, word choice. No single “correct” one. <a class="inl" data-go="craft">Lesson 7 →</a></p></div>
        </div>
        <div class="principle"><div class="pn">!</div><div><p style="margin:0"><strong>Diagnostic rule of thumb.</strong> When a draft feels flat, find which of the seven is underpowered. Nine times out of ten it’s conflict (too little) or causality (too loose).</p></div></div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============ 3 · CHARACTER ============ -->
    <section class="module" id="character" data-title="Character" data-phase="The Building Blocks" data-lesson="3">
      <div class="inner">
        <div class="mhead"></div>
        <p class="lead">Character is the engine: the protagonist should shape the plot, and the plot should shape the protagonist. Build them in this order.</p>

        <h3 id="ch-build"><span class="h3n">3.1</span>The build order</h3>
        <div class="stepper">
          <div class="step" data-n="1"><h4>Wants &amp; Needs</h4><p>Start here. What they <em>think</em> they want vs. what they truly need — the distance between is the shape of the inner journey.</p></div>
          <div class="step" data-n="2"><h4>Strengths &amp; Flaws</h4><p>Strengths make them <em>capable</em> of winning; flaws make them <em>relatable</em> and create real risk of failure. The reader must believe they could fail.</p></div>
          <div class="step" data-n="3"><h4>The necessary opponent</h4><p>Define the hero against others. The sharpest antagonist is the one best able to attack the hero’s deepest weakness — and who does so relentlessly.</p></div>
          <div class="step" data-n="4"><h4>Foils &amp; secondary cast</h4><p>A web in which each character defines the others. A foil throws the hero’s qualities into relief.</p></div>
          <div class="step" data-n="5"><h4>Look, behaviour, mannerisms</h4><p>Mannerisms are “show, don’t tell” in action — a braid-tug signals nerves without a word of narration.</p></div>
          <div class="step" data-n="6"><h4>Research their world</h4><p>Trade, slang, class, culture — until authentic detail surfaces. Consider sensitivity readers as research partners.</p></div>
        </div>

        <h3 id="ch-arc"><span class="h3n">3.2</span>The three arcs</h3>
        <p>Must a protagonist change? Not always — but they must be <strong>tested</strong>, and the reader must feel movement.</p>
        <div class="cardgrid cg-3">
          <div class="card">
            <svg class="spark" viewBox="0 0 140 58"><line x1="10" y1="50" x2="130" y2="50" stroke="var(--rule-soft)"/><path d="M12 47 C 56 45, 80 17, 128 9" stroke="var(--teal)"/><circle cx="12" cy="47" r="3" fill="var(--rule)"/><circle cx="128" cy="9" r="3.6" fill="var(--teal)"/></svg>
            <span class="sparkcap">starts low · ends transformed</span>
            <h4>Positive</h4><p>Learns the Need, overcomes the flaw. The most common shape. <em>(most heroes)</em></p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <svg class="spark" viewBox="0 0 140 58"><line x1="10" y1="50" x2="130" y2="50" stroke="var(--rule-soft)"/><path d="M12 38 C 42 14, 62 11, 80 19 C 100 30, 116 48, 128 52" stroke="var(--red)"/><circle cx="12" cy="38" r="3" fill="var(--rule)"/><circle cx="128" cy="52" r="3.6" fill="var(--red)"/></svg>
            <span class="sparkcap">rises · then falls further</span>
            <h4>Negative</h4><p>Fails to learn it; destroyed by the flaw. <em>(Gatsby, Macbeth)</em></p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <svg class="spark" viewBox="0 0 140 58"><line x1="10" y1="50" x2="130" y2="50" stroke="var(--rule-soft)"/><path d="M12 23 L128 23" stroke="var(--ochre)"/><path d="M12 47 C 60 47, 96 30, 128 26" stroke="var(--ochre)" stroke-opacity=".45" stroke-dasharray="3 3"/><circle cx="128" cy="23" r="3.6" fill="var(--ochre)"/></svg>
            <span class="sparkcap">hero steady — world shifts</span>
            <h4>Flat</h4><p>Hero holds steady (solid) and changes the <em>world</em> around them (dashed). <em>(Katniss, Atticus)</em></p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3 id="ch-gmc"><span class="h3n">3.3</span>A compact frame: G·M·C</h3>
        <div class="cardgrid cg-3">
          <div class="card"><span class="ico" style="color:var(--red)">G</span><h4>Goal</h4><p>What they’re pursuing (the Want).</p></div>
          <div class="card"><span class="ico" style="color:var(--ochre)">M</span><h4>Motivation</h4><p>Why they want it.</p></div>
          <div class="card"><span class="ico" style="color:var(--teal)">C</span><h4>Conflict</h4><p>What stands in the way.</p></div>
        </div>
        <p>State G·M·C for your protagonist <em>and</em> your antagonist and you have the skeleton of a dramatic situation.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============ 4 · CONFLICT ============ -->
    <section class="module" id="conflict" data-title="Conflict" data-phase="The Building Blocks" data-lesson="4">
      <div class="inner">
        <div class="mhead"></div>
        <p class="lead">Conflict is the fuel — it converts a goal into a story. Master two axes: the internal/external split, and the seven recurring types.</p>

        <h3 id="co-axes"><span class="h3n">4.1</span>Internal &amp; external — use both</h3>
        <div class="cardgrid cg-2">
          <div class="card" style="border-top:3px solid var(--red)"><span class="tag ext">external</span><h4>The world pushes back</h4><p>A rival, a storm, a corrupt system. The visible obstacle.</p></div>
          <div class="card" style="border-top:3px solid var(--teal)"><span class="tag int">internal</span><h4>The self pushes back</h4><p>A fear, a moral dilemma, a decision that threatens who they are.</p></div>
        </div>
        <div class="principle teal"><div class="pn">↔</div><div><p style="margin:0"><strong>Let the external dramatise the internal.</strong> Cheryl Strayed’s brutal hike in <em>Wild</em> mirrors her reckoning with grief and addiction. Whatever your outer conflict is, ask what inner struggle it makes visible.</p></div></div>

        <h3 id="co-types"><span class="h3n">4.2</span>The seven types</h3>
        <div class="tbl"><table>
          <thead><tr><th>Type</th><th></th><th>Core</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>Man vs. Man</strong></td><td><span class="tag ext">ext</span></td><td>Opposing goals; a mirror agenda</td><td><em>The Great Gatsby</em></td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Man vs. Society</strong></td><td><span class="tag ext">ext</span></td><td>The individual resists conformity</td><td><em>The Hate U Give</em></td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Man vs. Nature</strong></td><td><span class="tag ext">ext</span></td><td>Survival; can’t be reasoned with</td><td><em>The Martian</em></td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Man vs. Technology</strong></td><td><span class="tag ext">ext</span></td><td>The hubris of progress</td><td><em>Frankenstein</em></td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Man vs. Supernatural</strong></td><td><span class="tag both">both</span></td><td>Externalises human fear</td><td><em>Jekyll &amp; Hyde</em></td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Man vs. Fate</strong></td><td><span class="tag both">both</span></td><td>The fight against the inevitable</td><td><em>Macbeth</em></td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Man vs. Self</strong></td><td><span class="tag int">int</span></td><td>Inner dilemma; the deepest empathy</td><td><em>The Hunger Games</em></td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table></div>
        <div class="principle"><div class="pn">✦</div><div><p style="margin:0"><strong>The collapse insight.</strong> In stories without a human antagonist (vs. nature, vs. fate), the real conflict almost always collapses into <strong>Man vs. Self</strong>. The storm is just the stage the inner battle plays out on.</p></div></div>

        <h3 id="co-stakes"><span class="h3n">4.3</span>Stakes must escalate</h3>
        <p>Each obstacle should raise the cost of failure as the story proceeds. Flat-line tension bores; a staircase of rising pressure, with reversals, keeps pages turning — which is exactly what <a class="inl" data-go="structure">structure</a> organises.</p>
