    <!-- ============ 5 · STRUCTURE ============ -->
    <section class="module" id="structure" data-title="Structure" data-phase="The Building Blocks" data-lesson="5">
      <div class="inner">
        <div class="mhead"></div>
        <p class="lead">Structure is the order in which events reach the reader — the part of writing closest to engineering. Learn the universal shape first, then choose a framework as scaffolding.</p>

        <h3 id="st-arc"><span class="h3n">5.1</span>The universal story curve</h3>
        <p>Beneath every framework is one dramatic arc — tension rising across three acts. Tap a beat to see its job.</p>
        <div class="arcwrap">
          <svg class="arc-svg" id="arcsvg" viewBox="0 0 820 300" role="img" aria-label="The dramatic arc across three acts">
            <defs><linearGradient id="arcgrad" x1="0" x2="0" y1="0" y2="1"><stop offset="0" stop-color="#a23316" stop-opacity=".16"/><stop offset="1" stop-color="#a23316" stop-opacity="0"/></linearGradient></defs>
            <rect class="b1" x="42" y="46" width="173" height="226"/>
            <rect class="b2" x="215" y="46" width="430" height="226"/>
            <rect class="b3" x="645" y="46" width="155" height="226"/>
            <line class="sep" x1="215" y1="50" x2="215" y2="272"/>
            <line class="sep" x1="645" y1="50" x2="645" y2="272"/>
            <text class="actlbl" x="128" y="38">Act I · setup</text>
            <text class="actlbl" x="430" y="38">Act II · confrontation</text>
            <text class="actlbl" x="722" y="38">Act III · resolution</text>
            <line class="axis" x1="42" y1="272" x2="800" y2="272"/>
            <text class="axhint" x="42" y="288">time →</text>
            <text class="axhint" transform="translate(30,200) rotate(-90)" text-anchor="middle">tension →</text>
            <path class="area" fill="url(#arcgrad)" d="M60,250 C100,244 125,238 150,232 C190,224 220,222 250,210 C320,190 372,180 430,150 C492,120 512,110 540,114 C572,119 580,160 590,176 C620,150 652,96 680,60 C716,82 756,150 790,186 L790,272 L60,272 Z"/>
            <path class="curve" id="arccurve" d="M60,250 C100,244 125,238 150,232 C190,224 220,222 250,210 C320,190 372,180 430,150 C492,120 512,110 540,114 C572,119 580,160 590,176 C620,150 652,96 680,60 C716,82 756,150 790,186"/>
          </svg>
          <div class="arc-readout" id="arcReadout"><div class="rn">›</div><div><h4>The dramatic arc</h4><p>Tap any beat on the curve to see what it does and where it falls.</p></div></div>
        </div>

        <h3 id="st-beats"><span class="h3n">5.2</span>The beat vocabulary</h3>
        <p>Frameworks rename these, but the underlying beats are constant — learn them once and every model becomes legible. The two beginners most often misplace: land the <strong>inciting incident</strong> early, and use the <strong>midpoint</strong> to turn the hero from reacting to driving.</p>
        <div class="cardgrid cg-2">
          <div class="card"><h4>Inciting incident</h4><p>The catalyst that breaks the status quo and starts the real story. First ~10%.</p></div>
          <div class="card"><h4>Plot Point 1</h4><p>The hero commits and crosses the threshold into the new situation.</p></div>
          <div class="card"><h4>Rising action</h4><p>Escalating tests and complications — the bulk of the middle.</p></div>
          <div class="card"><h4>Midpoint</h4><p>A reversal that raises the stakes and flips the hero from passive to active.</p></div>
          <div class="card"><h4>Pinch points</h4><p>Pressure beats that remind us what the opposition is capable of.</p></div>
          <div class="card"><h4>All-Is-Lost · Plot Point 2</h4><p>The lowest point; the plan collapses and the old approach fails.</p></div>
          <div class="card"><h4>Climax</h4><p>The final confrontation, where the hard-won Need finally becomes usable.</p></div>
          <div class="card"><h4>Denouement</h4><p>Loose ends resolve and the new normal settles. Don’t skip it.</p></div>
        </div>

        <h3 id="st-frameworks"><span class="h3n">5.3</span>The framework explorer</h3>
        <p>Seven proven templates — variations on the same DNA. Pick one and click through its beats.</p>
        <div class="tabs" id="fwTabs"></div>
        <div class="explorer" id="fwExplorer"></div>

        <h3 id="st-pick"><span class="h3n">5.4</span>Which one should you use?</h3>
        <p>Start from your goal, not the catalogue. Click a goal to jump the explorer to its match.</p>
        <div class="matcher" id="matcher"></div>

        <div class="principle"><div class="pn">▲</div><div><p style="margin:0 0 6px"><strong>Scaffolding, not handcuffs.</strong> A cook follows the recipe exactly; a chef knows it well enough to deviate with intent.</p><p style="margin:0">Know the rules before you break them — for a first project, play them straight, then earn your deviations.</p></div></div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============ 6 · PROCESS ============ -->
    <section class="module" id="process" data-title="The Process" data-phase="Writing It" data-lesson="6">
      <div class="inner">
        <div class="mhead"></div>
        <p class="lead">Knowledge doesn’t write the book — this loop does. Six steps from blank page to finished draft.</p>

        <h3 id="pr-loop"><span class="h3n">6.1</span>The build loop</h3>
        <div class="flow">
          <div class="node"><span class="nn">01</span><h4>Character / concept</h4><p>Concept-first → plot-driven; character-first → character-driven. Choose consciously.</p></div>
          <div class="node"><span class="nn">02</span><h4>Inciting incident</h4><p>The catalyst that breaks the status quo. Introduce it early.</p></div>
          <div class="node"><span class="nn">03</span><h4>Rising action</h4><p>Most of your energy. Layer conflict, characterise constantly, plant twists.</p></div>
          <div class="node"><span class="nn">04</span><h4>Climax</h4><p>Conflict peaks; the critical choice; the Need becomes usable.</p></div>
          <div class="node"><span class="nn">05</span><h4>Ending</h4><p>Tie off threads, show the new normal, give closure.</p></div>
          <div class="node"><span class="nn">06</span><h4>Rewrite</h4><p>Break → reread → show-don’t-tell → ask what the story needs.</p></div>
        </div>

        <h3 id="pr-mode"><span class="h3n">6.2</span>Know your mode</h3>
        <div class="cardgrid cg-2">
          <div class="card"><h4>Plotter</h4><p>Outlines first, knows the ending. Lower risk of dead ends.</p></div>
          <div class="card"><h4>Pantser</h4><p>Discovers the story while writing, with only an approximate direction.</p></div>
        </div>
        <p>Most writers blend the two — and <strong>outlines are tools, not contracts</strong>. Once drafting begins, the story is primary: if it needs a scene the outline didn’t predict, write it.</p>

        <h3 id="pr-discipline"><span class="h3n">6.3</span>Drafting discipline</h3>
        <div class="cardgrid cg-2">
          <div class="card"><h4>Kill the inner editor</h4><p>On draft one, anything you put down beats the blank page.</p></div>
          <div class="card"><h4>Don’t write in order</h4><p>Stuck? Leave a gap, jump ahead, or write a scene in note form.</p></div>
          <div class="card"><h4>Finish the draft</h4><p>The hardest, most important act. A rough finished draft is fixable; a perfect first chapter is not a book.</p></div>
          <div class="card"><h4>Read in your genre</h4><p>The last 5–10 years, to absorb current pacing and conventions.</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============ 7 · CRAFT ============ -->
    <section class="module" id="craft" data-title="Sentence-Level Craft" data-phase="Writing It" data-lesson="7">
      <div class="inner">
        <div class="mhead"></div>
        <p class="lead">Structure gets the skeleton right; this is muscle and skin — the techniques that work line by line.</p>

        <h3 id="cr-show"><span class="h3n">7.1</span>Show, don’t tell</h3>
        <p>Don’t <em>report</em> emotion — <em>render</em> it through sense, action, and behaviour so the reader is present in the scene.</p>
        <div class="vs">
          <div class="v tell"><span class="vl">Telling</span>She was nervous.</div>
          <div class="v show"><span class="vl">Showing</span>She turned her coffee cup in slow circles, not drinking, her eyes flicking to the door each time it opened.</div>
        </div>

        <h3 id="cr-craftcards"><span class="h3n">7.2</span>The core techniques</h3>
        <div class="cardgrid cg-2">
          <div class="card"><h4>Dialogue</h4><p>Does double duty — advances plot <em>and</em> characterises. Subtext (what’s <em>not</em> said) often carries the most.</p></div>
          <div class="card"><h4>Exposition</h4><p>Necessary but dangerous. Drip it through action and dialogue; never dump it in slabs.</p></div>
          <div class="card"><h4>Foreshadowing</h4><p>A good twist is invisible forward, obvious in reverse. Plant clues; ration them; trust the reader.</p></div>
          <div class="card"><h4>The Rule of Three</h4><p>Three sets a pattern → rhythm and emphasis. Then break it with an “even” for contrast and resolution.</p></div>
        </div>

        <h3 id="cr-pov"><span class="h3n">7.3</span>Point of view</h3>
        <div class="tbl"><table>
          <thead><tr><th>POV</th><th>Feel</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>First (“I”)</strong></td><td>Most intimate</td><td>Common in short stories; can be unreliable</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Second (“you”)</strong></td><td>Unusual, immersive</td><td>Rare; high-risk, high-distinctiveness</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Third limited</strong></td><td>Close, slight distance</td><td>The modern workhorse</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Third omniscient</strong></td><td>Objective, formal</td><td>More distance; can head-hop if undisciplined</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table></div>
        <p>The <em>choice of which character narrates</em> can upend the whole plot — a murder told by the killer is a different book than one told by the detective. Whatever you pick, stay consistent: POV slips are a top beginner error.</p>

        <h3 id="cr-style"><span class="h3n">7.4</span>Style &amp; voice</h3>
        <p>There is no universal “good prose” — Hemingway’s terse sentences and Morrison’s lush imagery are both masterful. The goal is authenticity, not conformity. Voice emerges from writing a lot and reading widely; don’t manufacture it — uncover it.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============ 8 · FORMS ============ -->
    <section class="module" id="forms" data-title="Forms &amp; Constraints" data-phase="Writing It" data-lesson="8">
      <div class="inner">
        <div class="mhead"></div>
        <p class="lead">Same DNA, different containers. The constraints of a form decide what you cut and what you emphasise.</p>

        <h3 id="fm-scale"><span class="h3n">8.1</span>The length spectrum</h3>
        <div class="lenscale">
          <div class="lenrow"><div class="lenname"><span class="ll">Flash</span><span class="lw">&lt;1,000w</span></div><div class="lenbar" style="width:5%"></div></div>
          <div class="lenrow"><div class="lenname"><span class="ll">Short story</span><span class="lw">1k–10k</span></div><div class="lenbar" style="width:20%"></div></div>
          <div class="lenrow"><div class="lenname"><span class="ll">Novella</span><span class="lw">10k–40k</span></div><div class="lenbar" style="width:45%"></div></div>
          <div class="lenrow"><div class="lenname"><span class="ll">Novel</span><span class="lw">~80k+</span></div><div class="lenbar" style="width:92%"></div></div>
          <p class="lennote">A <strong>screenplay</strong> sits on a different axis entirely — measured in pages (~110), not words — because behaviour and image, not prose, carry the story.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="cardgrid cg-3">
          <div class="card"><h4>Short story</h4><p>One episode, one emotion. Few characters, single POV, one storyline, minimal backstory. Constraints are the art form.</p></div>
          <div class="card"><h4>Novel</h4><p>Room for multiple POVs, subplots, a B-story that carries theme. The cost is sustained momentum.</p></div>
          <div class="card"><h4>Screenplay</h4><p>Visual and external — the camera can’t hear thoughts. Everything shown through action and dialogue.</p></div>
        </div>

        <h3 id="fm-short"><span class="h3n">8.2</span>The short story, step by step</h3>
        <div class="stepper">
          <div class="step" data-n="1"><h4>Find the “first heartbeat”</h4><p>One capsule premise with a complex story latent inside (Kafka’s man who wakes as an insect).</p></div>
          <div class="step" data-n="2"><h4>A small, distinct cast</h4><p>Sometimes the <em>lack</em> of information about a character is what makes them compelling.</p></div>
          <div class="step" data-n="3"><h4>Begin close to the end</h4><p>Open <em>in medias res</em>. A great first line raises a question the reader needs answered.</p></div>
          <div class="step" data-n="4"><h4>Silence the inner editor</h4><p>Overwrite, leave gaps, write scenes as notes. Just reach a draft.</p></div>
          <div class="step" data-n="5"><h4>Land the ending</h4><p>True to the story’s logic but not predictable. Avoid both “Is that it?” and “What just happened?”</p></div>
          <div class="step" data-n="6"><h4>Edit, then beta-read</h4><p>Structural pass first, then line polish — then a friendly first audience.</p></div>
          <div class="step" data-n="7"><h4>Submit</h4><p>Literary magazines, contests, or self-publish. There’s no perfectly final draft.</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============ 9 · REVISION ============ -->
    <section class="module" id="revision" data-title="Revision &amp; Shipping" data-phase="Finishing" data-lesson="9">
      <div class="inner">
        <div class="mhead"></div>
        <p class="lead">A first draft is raw material, not a product. Revise from the coarsest layer to the finest — and know what readers expect before you ship.</p>

        <h3 id="rv-layers"><span class="h3n">9.1</span>Edit in layers</h3>
        <div class="funnel">
          <div class="flayer"><span class="fl">Pass 1 · coarse</span><h4>Structural / developmental</h4><p>Does the causal chain hold? Inciting incident early enough? Midpoint flips the hero active? Climax set up? Cut, add, reorder threads.</p></div>
          <div class="flayer"><span class="fl">Pass 2 · medium</span><h4>Line edit</h4><p>Rhythm, clarity, dialogue, show-don’t-tell, exposition pacing.</p></div>
          <div class="flayer"><span class="fl">Pass 3 · fine</span><h4>Polish &amp; proof</h4><p>Interrogate every word. “Is that what I mean? Could I say it better? Did I kill the clichés?”</p></div>
        </div>
        <p>Always <strong>take a break before editing</strong> — fresh eyes catch what tired ones can’t.</p>

        <h3 id="rv-traps"><span class="h3n">9.2</span>The beginner traps</h3>
        <div class="cardgrid cg-2">
          <div class="warn"><b>Starting too early.</b> Cramming setup before the story begins.</div>
          <div class="warn"><b>Exposition over action.</b> Telling instead of dramatising.</div>
          <div class="warn"><b>Weak motivation.</b> We don’t know why they want it.</div>
          <div class="warn"><b>Pacing wobble.</b> Rushing key beats, lingering on setup.</div>
          <div class="warn"><b>Flat dialogue.</b> Over-explaining; no subtext.</div>
          <div class="warn"><b>POV head-hopping.</b> The lens jumps without discipline.</div>
          <div class="warn"><b>“Done” = first draft.</b> Be your own editor first.</div>
          <div class="warn"><b>Template too literally.</b> A watered-down version of your own voice.</div>
        </div>

        <h3 id="rv-ship"><span class="h3n">9.3</span>Shipping routes</h3>
        <p><strong>Short fiction:</strong> literary magazines, contests, or self-publishing. <strong>Novels:</strong> traditional (agent → publisher; slow, often years) vs. self-publishing (faster, more control). Because traditional timelines are long, <strong>write the story you’re passionate about</strong> rather than chase a trend that may pass before you’re done. And know your genre’s <strong>absolutes</strong> — romance needs a happy/hopeful ending; MG and YA have firm age expectations. Break an absolute and you’re usually writing a different genre than you think.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============ 10 · CHEAT SHEET ============ -->
    <section class="module" id="cheatsheet" data-title="The Cheat Sheet" data-phase="Reference" data-lesson="10">
      <div class="inner wide">
        <div class="mhead"></div>
        <div class="bigquote">A character <strong>wants</strong> something; an <strong>obstacle</strong> stands in the way; the pursuit <strong>changes them.</strong></div>
        <div class="cardgrid cg-3">
          <div class="card"><h4>The five laws</h4><ol style="margin:0;padding-left:1.1em;font-size:14.5px"><li>Therefore, not “and then.”</li><li>Conflict is story.</li><li>Want vs. Need.</li><li>Show, don’t tell.</li><li>Finish the draft.</li></ol></div>
          <div class="card"><h4>The seven elements</h4><p style="font-size:14.5px;margin:0">Theme · Character · Setting · Plot · Conflict · POV · Style</p></div>
          <div class="card"><h4>Character order</h4><p style="font-size:14.5px;margin:0">Wants &amp; Needs → Strengths &amp; Flaws → Necessary opponent → Foils → Look → Research → Arc. Frame: G·M·C.</p></div>
          <div class="card"><h4>Universal beats</h4><p style="font-size:14.5px;margin:0">Inciting incident (early!) → Plot Point 1 → Midpoint → Pinch → All-Is-Lost → Dark Night → Climax → Denouement.</p></div>
          <div class="card"><h4>The six-step build</h4><p style="font-size:14.5px;margin:0">Character/concept → Inciting incident → Rising action → Climax → Ending → Rewrite.</p></div>
          <div class="card"><h4>Frameworks at a glance</h4><p style="font-size:14px;margin:0">Three-Act · default. Hero’s Journey · quests. Save the Cat · scripts. Seven-Point · design from the end. Story Circle · series. Fichtean · fast start. Freytag · tragedy.</p></div>
        </div>
        <h4 style="font-family:var(--display);font-size:22px;margin:34px 0 6px">Pre-ship checklist</h4>
        <ul class="checklist" style="columns:2;column-gap:34px">
          <li>Inciting incident in first ~10%</li>
          <li>Every transition is “therefore / but”</li>
          <li>Internal <em>and</em> external conflict present</li>
          <li>Midpoint flips the hero to active</li>
          <li>Climax is set up, not arbitrary</li>
          <li>Denouement delivers closure</li>
          <li>POV consistent</li>
          <li>Exposition dripped, not dumped</li>
          <li>Clichés cut</li>
          <li>Slept on it, then edited in layers</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

